# All the things she sent

## Flag 01

We start with an Android `.apk` and iOS `.ipa` file. Disassembling the Android app with [JADX](https://github.com/skylot/jadx) we learn that it's a React Native app using something called "Hermes bytecode."

I used [`hermes-dec`](https://github.com/P1sec/hermes-dec) to disassemble the bytecode.

We find references to two URLs:
- https://muemmelmoehre-mobile2025.challenges.hfctf.ca:9876/
- wss://muemmelmoehre-mobile2025.challenges.hfctf.ca:8765/ws

The first URL is an API. Sending a `GET` request to `https://muemmelmoehre-mobile2025.challenges.hfctf.ca:9876/activate` yields a PNG blob containing the first flag.

## Flag 02

Initiating a WebSocket connection with `websocat` yields the second flag:

```console
[MacBook-Pro ~]$ websocat wss://muemmelmoehre-mobile2025.challenges.hfctf.ca:8765/ws

{"err":"Sorry, invalid json.","misc":" Please try again. Meanwhile, have a flag: HF-d9fa3c76ea6237d17209a85df890d789"}
```

## The Search for Flag 03

I installed the Android app on my phone. There's a WebSocket console where you can see the app sends the following payload to the WebSocket:

```json
{"fingerprint":"unknownModel|16|noInstallId", "ts": 1760663781998, "nonce": "9ljdyxip"}
```

The WebSocket returns with an AES256 encrypted payload:

```json
{"enc":{"iv":"xve4o50kkBlNEYLQ","ct":"","tag":"3tbwkaa/1yV2un8K2tt6Ew=="},"ts":1760663781998,"nonce":"9ljdyxip"}
```

There's a hint in the mobile app that says:

> Connect for secure AES-GCM encrypted goodies! Our server uses SHA256 to hash your message.
>
> Note to our developer: Have you implemeted the use of nonces yet?

I spent time but couldn't figure out how to decrypt the payload.
